ins of design history. From the sensually gendered role of the fireplace in late sixteenth century Italy to the synaesthetic décors of Comte Robert de Montesquiou and the sensorial stimuli of Aesop stores, each chapter brings a new perspective on the central role that the senses have played in the conception, experiences and uses of interiors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aInterior decorationxHistory. 0aSenses and sensation in interior decoration. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aARCHITECTURE / Interior Design / General.2bisacsh  a1925 Paris Exhibition.  aBlack Deco.  aHerrenzimmer.  aNazi propaganda.  aPierre Legrain.  aTerence Conran.  adesign history.  adomestic interior.  ahearing.  ainterior design.  amiddle-class home.  aqueer photography.  asensory politics.  asensory studies.  asensual economies.  asight.  asmell.  asynaesthesia.  ataste.  atouch.1 aBeaulieu, Benoit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaulieu, Benoit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Erin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeaville, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Alice T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHighmore, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowes, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuppatz, D. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIarocci, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLees-Maffei, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r